==Japanese==

===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|alt=灰汁}}

Likely derived from verb {{m|ja|あきる|飽きる・厭きる・倦きる|tr=akiru}}, older form {{m|ja|[[飽く]]・[[厭く]]・[[倦く]]|tr=aku||to be full up; to be fully done; to tire of something, to have too much of something}}.<ref name="GYJ">"{{lang|ja|[https://gogen-yurai.jp/aku/ 灰汁]}}" in {{m|ja||語源由来辞典|tr=Gogen Yurai Jiten|Etymology Derivation Dictionary}} (in Japanese)</ref>

First cited to the {{m|ja||{{w|lang=ja|古今和歌集}}|tr={{w|Kokin Wakashū}}}} of the early 900s,<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2|灰汁}}</ref> where the term is used as a [[pun]] for the verb.<ref name="GYJ"/>

The senses related to {{m|en|flavor}} and {{m|en|harshness}} arose from the practice of using [[lye]] in food processing to remove unpleasant flavors.<ref name="GYJ"/>

The kanji spelling {{m|ja|灰汁}} is an example of [[jukujikun]], using the characters for {{m|ja|灰||[[ash]]}} and {{m|ja|汁||[[broth]]}} in reference to the practice of [[leach]]ing wood ash in water to derive [[lye]].

